    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, the classic hollandaise disaster! It happens when the emulsion breaks, usually because the butter got too hot or the egg yolk was too cold, causing the fat to separate from the water-based yolk. It's a bit like a goblin trying to hold a heavy sack of gold in one hand while running away from a dragon; if they get too stressed or the bag gets too hot, the gold just spills out onto the cobblestones, leaving the goblin covered in grease and the road slick with oil.\n\nThe good news is that it's rarely truly ruined, though it certainly tastes like a sad, greasy puddle right now. You can try to save it by gently whisking in a tiny bit of hot water or even a splash of lemon juice to re-emulsify the fat, but honestly, it's often easier to just start fresh. Think of it like a goblin who accidentally drops their treasure chest in a river; you can try to scoop the gold back out with a net, but usually, it's just more fun to grab a new chest and move on.\n\nFor your next attempt, make sure your butter is at room temperature and your egg yolk is warm, and whisk them",
